<TITLE> ACC sues four BNP and AL leaders </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 24 (bdnews24.com)The Anticorruption Commission has filed four separate cases against former BNP minister Shajahan Siraj and three former Awami League lawmakers Sheikh Helal Uddin, Haji Selim and Kamal Ahmed Majumder. Four ACC officials filed the four cases with Ramna and Lalbag police stations in the capital Monday. The cases have been filed under the emergency powers rules and the Criminal Procedure Code. ACC assistant director Khairul Huda filed the case against former jute and textiles minister Shajahan Siraj and wife Rabeya Siraj with Ramna police. Shajahan Siraj is accused of earning wealth worth Tk 68.50 lakh beyond his known income. Rabeya is accused in the case of concealing information about a bank balance of Tk 65,992. Shajahan is currently in jail, serving eight years in another case. Lalbagh police told bdnews24.com that the ACC had filed a case against Haji Selim and wife Gulshan Ara, in which they are accused of owning wealth worth Tk 14.65 crore beyond their known income and concealing information about Tk 8.7 crore in wealth. Selim has been fugitive since the imposition of the state of emergency. Ramna police told bdnews24.com that the case filed against Kamal Ahmed Majumder alleges that he earned Tk 10 crore beyond his known income and suppressed information about property worth Tk 7.19 crore. The case also accused his wife Shahida Kamal. ACC deputy director Monzur Ahmed filed the case against Awami League leader Helal and wife Rupa Chowdhury. The case accuses Helal of illegal earnings worth Tk 7.6 crore in his own and wife's names, through corruption and misuse of power. Allegations of giving false information in their wealth statement to the ACC have also been brought against them. bdnews24.com/mim/
